map_node.indicator_name: PM<sub>2.5</sub>-Attributable Cardiovascular Hospitalizations (Adults 40 Yrs and Older)
map_node.indicator_description: PM2.5-attributable cardiovascular hospitalizations represent part of the health burden imposed by fine particle air pollution.

dataset.how_calculated: Estimate is based on the number of hospitalizations for cardiovascular causes associated with the difference in air quality for indicator years relative to natural background (modeled air quality levels under no man-made air pollution emissions). Estimate is calculated using the acute risk of hospitalizations for all cardiovascular causes from the Ito K et al 2010 study conducted on New York City residents above 40 years of age. Neighborhood estimates expressed as annual cases per 100,000 residents over 40 years of age.
dataset.discription: New York State Statewide Planning and Research Cooperative System (SPARCS); US Census,US EPA Air Quality System; Ito K et al (2011) Environ Hlth Persp, 119(4):467-473

show_disparities_node.disparitiesPagetext: When population health or the quality of living environments varies by population characteristics such as income or race, there is disparity. One way to visualize disparity is to chart indicators of health or environment across levels of neighborhood poverty. We categorized neighborhoods as high, medium or low poverty. Then we took the median of the neighborhood-specific values in each category. The median is the middle of the sorted group of values.
